South African Stock Preview: Avusa, Cashbuild, Kaydav, Poynting, Primeserv

-- B y   A n a   M o n t e i r o
-- 
2011-03-28T22:00:00Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-28/south-african-stock-preview-avusa-cashbuild-kaydav-poynting.html
The following may rise or fall in
 South Africa . Symbols are in parentheses and prices are from the
last close.  The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index declined for a second
day, falling 218.77, or 0.7 percent, to 31,377.12 in
Johannesburg.  Accentuate Ltd. (ACE)  : The cleaning and maintenance
company expects to report a loss of 27 cents to 32 cents a share
for the six months through December from earnings of 8.31 cents
a share a year earlier today. The stock closed unchanged at 59
cents.  Avusa Ltd. (AVU)  : South Africa’s No. 2 newspaper
publisher that runs a publishing venture with Pearson Plc in
South Africa said it received an unsolicited offer for all of
its shares from a group represented by Capitau Holdings Ltd.,
RMB Ventures and other unidentified investors. The company will
consider the bid, it said in statement after the market closed
yesterday. The shares added 3.89 rand, or 18 percent, to 25
rand.  Cashbuild Ltd. (CSB)  : The building materials retailer
expects to announce earnings per share for the half year through
December will be 20 percent to 25 percent lower than a year
earlier today. The stock increased 4.94 rand, or 5.4 percent, to
96.44 rand.  Kaydav Group Ltd. (KDV)  : The wood board distributor and
wholesaler said net income for the year through December climbed
to 14.6 million rand from 10.7 million rand a year earlier. The
shares were unchanged at 38 cents.  Poynting Holdings Ltd. (POY)  : The company that makes
telecommunications and military antennas expects to report a
loss per share of 2.90 cents to 3.41 cents from the six months
through December from earnings per share of 2.55 cents a year
earlier. The stock was unchanged at 21 cents.  Primeserv Group Ltd. (PMV)  : The training-center
management company’s Primeserv Staff Dynamix (Pty) Ltd. unit
will pay 5.5 million rand to compensate customers of HRS for
ending temporary employment service agreements with them. The
shares were unchanged at 37 cents.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ana Monteiro in Johannesburg at 
